The prompt: your most powerful tool Of everything you&rsquo;ll learn in this course, the ability to write good prompts is probably the most useful day to day. A good prompt can be the difference between a useless response and a brilliant one — with the same model.
A prompt is simply the text you send to the model. Your question, your instructions, the context you provide. Everything you type in a chatbot&rsquo;s text box is a prompt.
Why does it matter how you ask? Remember from Lesson 6: an LLM generates text by predicting the most probable word given the input. If the input is vague, the output will be vague. If the input is specific and clear, the output will be much better.
Let&rsquo;s compare two prompts for the same task:
Bad prompt: &ldquo;Explain AI to me&rdquo;
Too broad. The model doesn&rsquo;t know what level to explain at, how long it should be, or which aspect of AI you&rsquo;re interested in.
Good prompt: &ldquo;Explain what artificial intelligence is in 3 short paragraphs. The audience is an adult with no technical background. Use everyday examples like smartphones or Netflix.&rdquo;
Now the model knows exactly what you want: length, level, and style.
The four pieces of a good prompt 1. Role Tell the model who it is or what role to adopt.
&ldquo;You are a computer science teacher who explains concepts to people with no technical background.&rdquo;
2. Context Give it the information it needs to respond well.
&ldquo;I&rsquo;m preparing a presentation for my company&rsquo;s directors. They have no technical background but they make budget decisions.&rdquo;
3. Instruction Tell it exactly what you want it to do.
&ldquo;Write me 5 key points about why we should invest in AI, with a concrete example for each point.&rdquo;
4. Output format Tell it how you want the response.
&ldquo;Respond as a numbered list. Each point should have a bold title followed by a 2-3 line explanation.&rdquo;
Practical examples Task: Write an email
Basic prompt: &ldquo;Write an email to my boss about holidays&rdquo;
Improved prompt: &ldquo;Write a short, professional email to my boss, Jordi, asking for 3 days off the week of June 15th. The tone should be friendly but direct. Mention that I&rsquo;ll leave pending tasks organised.&rdquo;
Task: Understand a concept
Basic prompt: &ldquo;What is blockchain?&rdquo;
Improved prompt: &ldquo;Explain what blockchain is as if you were explaining it to someone who can use a computer but can&rsquo;t program. Use an everyday analogy. Maximum 200 words.&rdquo;
Common mistakes Being too vague: &ldquo;Help me with my project&rdquo; — What project? What help?
Doing too many things at once: Better to go step by step.
Assuming it knows everything: &ldquo;Do what I told you yesterday&rdquo; — The model doesn&rsquo;t remember previous conversations.
Not specifying the format: If you don&rsquo;t say how you want the response, the model will choose for itself.
Prompt engineering: no programming required The term prompt engineering sounds very technical, but it simply means &ldquo;the art of writing good prompts&rdquo;. It&rsquo;s not programming — it&rsquo;s clear, precise communication.
Some useful techniques:
Few-shot prompting: Give it examples of what you want. &ldquo;Convert these titles into URL slugs. Example: &lsquo;What is AI?&rsquo; → &lsquo;what-is-ai&rsquo;. Now do it for: &lsquo;How does an LLM work?&rsquo;&rdquo;
Chain of thought: Ask it to reason step by step. &ldquo;Before giving the final answer, explain your reasoning step by step.&rdquo;
Iteration: Don&rsquo;t expect the first prompt to be perfect. Try it, look at the result, and adjust.
The prompt is the interface Think of the prompt as the interface between you and the model. An excellent model with a bad prompt will give a mediocre result. A decent model with an excellent prompt can give a surprisingly good result.
When you configure your agent with OpenClaw, the system prompt will be the most important piece of the entire configuration. Investing time in it is well worth it.
Key concepts today Prompt: The text you send to the model — question, instructions, context The 4 pieces: Role + Context + Instruction + Output format Prompt engineering: The art of writing effective prompts (no programming required) Few-shot: Giving the model examples so it understands the desired format Chain of thought: Asking the model to reason step by step to improve accuracy Iteration: Adjusting the prompt based on results until you get what you want Next lesson: We start Week 3 — What is a provider? Who gives you access to models.

The system prompt: your agent&rsquo;s DNA If the model is the brain and the tools are the hands, the system prompt is the personality. It defines how the agent behaves: what language it speaks, what tone it uses, what rules it follows, what it knows about you.
Two agents with the same model and tools can be completely different if they have different system prompts.
Where to configure it In OpenClaw, the system prompt is a Markdown file at ~/.openclaw/workspace/system-prompt.md.
Structure of a good system prompt 1. Identity &ldquo;You are a personal assistant specialising in technology. Your name is Atlas. You&rsquo;re direct and practical.&rdquo;
2. Behaviour &ldquo;Always respond in English. Use technical terms naturally. Be concise.&rdquo;
3. Context &ldquo;The user is an IT professional with experience in Linux and Docker.&rdquo;
4. Limits &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t give medical or legal advice. If a request is ambiguous, ask for clarification.&rdquo;
Tips Be specific. &ldquo;Be friendly&rdquo; is vague. &ldquo;Respond in a warm tone, as if talking to a colleague&rdquo; is concrete.
Iterate. The first system prompt won&rsquo;t be perfect. Use it for a few days, identify what you don&rsquo;t like, and adjust.
Don&rsquo;t overload it. A 3,000-word system prompt consumes tokens with every message.
Language matters. Write it in the language you want responses in.
Key concepts today System prompt: Permanent instructions defining personality and behaviour ~/.openclaw/workspace/system-prompt.md: Where the system prompt lives in OpenClaw Four parts: Identity + Behaviour + Context + Limits Iterate: It improves with use Next lesson: We start Week 6 — Essential skills for your agent.
